AB The sorption properties of TiO2 nanoparticles (NPs) on sand were
   investigated in the presence of Suwannee River humic acid (SRHA) as a
   surrogate for natural organic matter. SRHA drastically reduced the
   sorption preference regardless of the initial pH and ionic strength of
   the solution. Despite the higher SRHA loading onto sand versus the TiO2
   NPs, the consequent zeta (zeta)-potential drop was more significant in
   the TiO2 NPs, indicating that the decreased sorption should be primarily
   ascribed to the fraction of SRHA sorbed onto the TiO2 NP surfaces. The
